Therefore, the answer is \boxed{5 \times 10^{-24}} meters. **Final Answer** The de Broglie wavelength of the baseball is \boxed{5 \times 10^{-24}} meters. </think> To find the de Broglie wavelength of the baseball, we use the formula: \[ \lambda = \frac{h}{p} = \frac{h}{mv} \] where: - \( h \) is Planck's constant (\( 6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s} \)), - \( m \) is the mass of the baseball (\( 145 \, \text{g} = 0.145 \, \text{kg} \)), - \( v \) is the velocity of the baseball (\( 1 \, \text{nm/s} = 1 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m/s} \)). First, we calculate the momentum \( p \): \[ p = mv = 0.145 \, \text{kg} \times 1 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m/s} = 1.45 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{kg·m/s} \] Next, we use Planck's constant to find the wavelength: \[ \lambda = \frac{6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}}{1.45 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{kg·m/s}} \] Converting the units and performing the division: \[ \lambda = \frac{6.62607015 \times 10^{-34}}{1.45 \times 10^{-10}} = \frac{6.62607015}{1.45} \times 10^{-24} \approx 4.566 \times 10^{-24} \, \text{m} \] Considering the significant figures, the velocity is given as \( 1 \, \text{nm/s} \) (1 significant figure), which is the limiting factor. Therefore, we round the result to 1 significant figure: \[ \lambda \approx 5 \times 10^{-24} \, \text{m} \] Thus, the de Broglie wavelength of the baseball is \(\boxed{5 \times 10^{-24}}\) meters.
